Life as a Writer -- tWhose Loud Fast Rules? – Always Already Post-Hardcore -- t“Have You Never Been Mellow?” – Joy and Ugliness in Punk and Hardcore Aesthetics -- tQueer-feminist Hardcore/Punk: Academic Research and Community Support in the Age of the Pandemic -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgements0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor more than 40 years, hardcore and punk have promised to offer an alternative to what is perceived as the norm and the mainstream. Hardcore Research: Punk, Practice, Politics provides a comprehensive insight into some of the most active, outspoken, and widely received scholarly positions in the academic discourses on hardcore and punk and combines them with a variety of new and emerging voices. The book brings together scholars with personal ties to past and present hardcore and punk scenes, who present both insightful and critical examinations of the rich and varied histories of this subcultural phenomenon and its current reverberations at the intersection of cultural practice and academic research.  afunded by Paris Lodron Universität Salzburg  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHardcore (Music)xHistory and criticism. 0aPunk culture. 0aPunk rock musicxHistory and criticism. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCulture. 4aMusic History. 4aMusic. 4aPop Music. 4aPopular Culture. 4aPunk. 4aSubculture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aCulture.  aMusic History.  aMusic.  aPop Music.  aPopular Culture.  aPunk.  aSubculture.1 aAmbrosch, Gerfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernhard, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBestley, Russ, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/